INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_0300_L105$$, 2026, $$The AC/MC-130J Line Item funds the rapid fielding of advanced strike and survivability capabilities for Special Operations Forces (SOF) AC-130J and MC-130J aircraft as modernized replacements for the retired
 AC-130U/H/W and MC-130E/P/H fleets. AC-130J "Ghostrider" aircraft perform strike missions, to include close air support (CAS), air interdiction, and armed reconnaissance missions. MC-130J "Commando
 II" aircraft perform SO-peculiar (SO-p) mobility missions, to include clandestine, or low visibility, single or multiship, low-level infiltration (infil), exfiltration (exfil), and resupply of SOF, by airdrop or airland and air
 refueling for SOF helicopters and tiltrotor aircraft, intruding politically sensitive or hostile territories.

 The United States Air Force procures and fields the basic C-130J aircraft, common support equipment, and Weapon System Trainers (WST). The United States Special Operations Command (USSOCOM)
 modifies the basic C-130J aircraft and WSTs with mission systems that provide SO-p capabilities integrated through the Special Mission System, and procures standalone training devices for specialized SO-
 p mission training. Rapid fielding and incremental upgrades are used to integrate SOF mission systems onto the basic C-130J aircraft that provide SO-p strike and mobility capabilities, with the objective to
 integrate and automate aircrew responsibilities to reduce workload. For MC-130J, these SO-p capabilities include Airborne Mission Networking (AbMN) to connect into the Department of Defense Joint All-
 Domain Command and Control construct, provide data fusion and improved situational awareness. Additionally, integration of the Silent Knight Radar (SKR) enables integrated terrain following (TF) / terrain
 avoidance (TA) for infil/exfil in contested operations, and a defensive countermeasures (DCM) suite with integrated electronic warfare (EW) capability increases survivability through enhanced threat detection
 and response. MC-130J Commando II aircraft that receive AbMN, TF/TA, and RFCM SO-p modifications are designated with the popular name "Combat Talon III."

 Integrating and automating SOF mission systems that deliver these capabilities is critical to fielding SOF-capable AC-130J and MC-130J aircraft to recapitalize the retired USSOCOM C-130 fleet, reduce the
 required crew complement for the changing operational environment and allow SOF to be more lethal, resilient, survivable, agile, and responsive. This budget line item also funds AC/MC-130J efforts related to
 communications security and joint/coalition interoperability, such as cryptographic modernization and low-cost modifications (LCM) to improve reliability, maintainability, mission effectiveness, and safety.

 The Precision Strike Package (PSP) for Special Operations Forces (SOF), Program Number 843, funds the procurement, installation, and rapid fielding of the PSP onto the AC-130J and various SOF platforms
 and training devices to provide a close air support, air interdiction, and armed reconnaissance capability including sensors, communications systems, precision guided munition systems, mission operator pallet,
 and gun systems. In FY 2027, the PSP program will continue to modernize, enhance the PSP baseline through software capability improvements, and procure and install Active Electronic Scanned Array (AESA)
 Radars. The Mission Optimization Modification effort is projected to complete 4th QTR FY 2027.

 This line item received a FY 2026 $15.000 million Congressional Add for Airborne Mission Networking Upgrades.$$, NULL, $$Exhibit P-40, Budget Line Item Justification: PB 2027 United States Special Operations Command                                                                                 Date: April 2026
