 Description:
 Teleport: The DoW Teleport Program acquires, modernizes, and sustains joint Satellite Communications (SATCOM) capabilities to connect the warfighter to the DoW Information Network (DoWIN) and the
 Defense Information System Network (DISN). The DoW Teleport System connects the deployed warfighters (air, ground, and sea) to their domains via SATCOM. It also provides access to DISN services
 including Secret Internet Protocol Router Network (SIPRNet), Non-classified Internet Protocol Router Network (NIPRNet), Defense Red Switch Network (DRSN), Defense Switched Network (DSN), and access to
 Enterprise Voice over Internet Protocol (EVoIP), Enterprise Classified Voice over Internet Protocol (ECVoIP), and other services.

 The Teleport Program is a Category III Acquisition Program, which began in the early 2000s and is currently in the final phases of its third Generation. Generation-I and Generation-II built SATCOM Terminals
 and Network Equipment. Generation-III Phase-1 fielded Advanced Extremely High Frequency SATCOM terminals. Generation-III Phase-2 modernized legacy enterprise X-band SATCOM terminals, replacing
 them with X/Ka-band SATCOM terminals. Generation-III Phase-3 has focused on interoperability between Mobile User Objective System (MUOS) SATCOM users and legacy Ultra-High Frequency (UHF)
 SATCOM users. Teleport requires procurement funding to keep its existing SATCOM and Network infrastructure modern, interoperable, and responsive (Teleport Technology Refresh). It also requires
 procurement funding to deliver Generation-III Phase-3 MUOS to Legacy UHF interoperability capability. Lastly, procurement funding is required to field Integrated Waveform (IW) upgrade to the Teleport UHF
 system, U.S.- MUOS to Legacy Gateway Component (MLGC) expansion, and allied MLGC expansion.

 Prior to FY 2025, Standardized Tactical Entry Point (STEP) and SATCOM Gateway, two legacy programs which pre-date Teleport, also had satellite equipment at various global locations, some overlapping with
 Teleport. During FY 2025, DISA converged the STEP and SATCOM Gateway programs and capabilities under the DoW Teleport Program. This reduced duplication and enabled DISA to provide unified Teleport
 capabilities at 16 sites worldwide. Some of the Teleports are large sites with multiple SATCOM terminals enabling connection to multiple frequency bands; many of the new Teleport sites are small sites with one
 or two terminals connecting to one or two frequency bands.

 A Joint SATCOM Teleport site consists of SATCOM terminals (antennas, satellite dishes) that transmit and receive Warfighter Radio Frequency (RF) communications, SATCOM modems that modulate and
 demodulate the warfighter data communications stream, and network equipment (routers, switches, firewalls, and servers) that route and transport warfighter data communications to their domain as well as
 provide access to DISN services. Large Teleport sites have multiple SATCOM terminals that operate in different frequency bands to support warfighter requirements: wideband, protected band, and narrow
 band. Teleport wideband terminals operate on Military SATCOM and Commercial SATCOM satellite constellations including Wideband Global SATCOM (WGS) X-band and Ka-band, commercial C-band, and
 commercial Ku-band. Teleport protected band SATCOM terminals operate on Military Strategic and Tactical Relay (MILSTAR) and Advanced Extremely High Frequency satellite constellations. The Teleport
 System is in a constant state of technology refresh to upgrade to new technologies, replace end-of-life/end-of-support equipment, and address cybersecurity orders. For example, one year it may need to refresh
 SATCOM modems at all Joint SATCOM Teleport sites; another year it may need to upgrade the satellite dishes and radio frequency equipment for wideband SATCOM terminals.


