INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_0300_L037$$, 2027, $$DoDNet is a strategic initiative to consolidate and standardize the DoW information technology environment. Directed by the Deputy Secretary of War in the August 2019 "Fourth Estate Network Optimization
 Execution Guidance" memorandum, DoDNet aims to unify disparate networks across the DoW.

 The Defense Information Systems Agency (DISA) has been designated as the DoW's Single Service Provider (SSP) for DoDNet. DISA is actively consolidating commodity Information Technology (IT) Local Area
 Networks (LANs) and service desks for 14 (now 16) initial Defense Agencies and Field Activities (DAFAs). DISA was able to add the Defense Security Cooperation Agency (DSCA) and separated the Strategic
 Capabilities Office (SCO) from the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) increasing the number of Phase I DAFAs from 14 to 16. Upon migration, each DAFA will operate within this common
 IT environment, utilizing DoDNet as its primary network. This migration inherently advances Zero Trust compliance, as DAFAs joining DoDNet will immediately gain Thunderdome Zero Trust capabilities. In
 the future, DISA plans to expand DoDNet to include additional DAFAs and Combatant Commands. This enterprise-wide migration directly supports the DoW's priority of "Rebuilding the Military" by fostering
 maximum efficiency, effectiveness, and significantly reducing redundancies and waste across the Department.

 The iterative migration process spans multiple fiscal years and involves several key stages:
 • Site Surveys: Comprehensive virtual and physical assessments of legacy networks.
 • Planning and Design: Identification of necessary equipment upgrades based on survey findings.
 • Equipment Procurement: Acquisition of modern hardware and software (procurement is initiated only when DISA is ready to purchase specific equipment for a DAFA's migration).
 • Installation: Deployment of new and replacement equipment.
 • Integration: Seamless incorporation of new and existing standardized equipment into the DoDNet architecture.
 • User Migration: Transition of personnel to the new network.

 Given the varying quality of DAFA IT infrastructure, connecting to DoDNet often necessitates significant modern equipment upgrades. Post-migration, DAFAs require ongoing technical refreshes to ensure
 continuous effective and secure network operations. DISA has already begun technical refreshes for equipment purchased in FY 2021, including for DISA itself, the Defense Prisoner of War/Missing in Action
 (POW/MIA) Accounting Agency (DPAA), and the Defense Technical Information Center (DTIC). Continuous technical refresh is paramount for maintaining a seamless user experience and robust security.

 To enable seamless user access and DAFA connectivity, DoDNet Service Centers require up-to-date servers, IT infrastructure, and periodic equipment refreshes. DoDNet Service Centers connect the DAFAs to
 the DoDNet interface. DoDNet cannot operate without them.$$, NULL, $$Exhibit P-40, Budget Line Item Justification: PB 2027 Defense Information Systems Agency                                                                                       Date: April 2026
