 Description:
 The 2.75 inch Rocket variant is a versatile system that can be employed across multiple platforms including rotor and fixed wing aircraft, naval vessels, and ground platforms in the Close Air Support (CAS),
 Military Operations in Urban Terrain (MOUT), counter-Fast Attack Craft/Fast Inshore Attack Craft (counter-FAC/FIAC), and Counter-UAS (C-UAS) mission areas. The 2.75-inch rocket configured with Advanced
 Precision Kill Weapon System (APKWS) Guidance Sections enable a resilient and precise weapon in support of close combat lethality in complex terrain.

 Combat and training inventory requirements for rocket and rocket components establish the Total Munitions Requirement (TMR) in accordance with the Naval Munitions Requirements Process (NMRP).
 Production is for complete units/operationally-configured units to satisfy the requirement of applicable specifications of Airborne Rockets, All types. Airborne Rockets supports both Navy and Marine Corps.

 APKWS can be outfitted with a variety of fuzes and warheads, such as point detonating and proximity fuzes, the Mk-152 Insensitive Munitions (IM) compliant warhead for shipboard operations with APKWS
 guidance sections and the M282 Multi-Purpose Penetrator (MPP) warhead among many others, provides fleet users unmatched operational flexibility, improved target-mission matching for specific applications
 and effects, and permits logistic agility. In testing, inert warheads are used extensively when range restrictions preclude live applications.

 APKWS is a low-cost Semi-Active Laser (SAL) guidance section to enhance the precision of 2.75-inch unguided rockets. APKWS is a small, lightweight, mid-body guidance section that can be assembled
 with existing unguided rocket components and can be fired from 2.75-inch rocket launchers. Compared to unguided rockets, APKWS sustains the Joint Force military advantage by offering greater precision,
 increased stored kills per aircraft sortie, reduces collateral damage, improves effectiveness against soft and lightly armored targets, Counter Unmanned Aerial Systems (C-UAS) targets utilizing a proximity fuze,
 and enhances close-combat lethality and crew survivability through increased standoff ranges for platforms both air and afloat.

 Rocket Launchers provide guided and unguided rocket launch capability for 2.75-inch Rockets including the LAU-61 G/A Digital Rocket Launcher (DRL), LAU-61 C/A, and LAU-68 F/A.

 A variety of containers are required to support shipping, handling, and storage of all-up-round rockets and rocket components. The program re-manufactures existing containers and procures new containers, as
 needed.

 The Smokey Sam Simulator System is a pyrotechnic visual cueing device primarily utilized in aircrew training to mimic a Surface-to-Air Missile threat. The system is qualified for use on both land and at sea.

 Miscellaneous Items provides for procurement of various rocket components not to exceed a total cost of $0.500M per year, per component.


