INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_3010_L046$$, 2026, $$The F-22 Raptor is a multi-mission fighter aircraft that combines low observability, supercruise, maneuverability and integrated avionics providing air superiority to the Joint Force, access in highly contested
 environments, as well as homeland and cruise missile defense with service life into the 2040s. Currently, the force structure plan is comprised of 185 aircraft in the F-22 fleet, consisting of 32 Block 20 and 153
 Block 30/35 by the end of FY25. The average age of the fleet is 16.96 years. To maintain operational relevance, the program continues planned, incremental modernization efforts that enhance both F-22 air
 superiority and strike capabilities. The F-22 modernization enterprise develops, tests, and fields hardware/software of the air vehicle, engine, Operational Flight Program (OFP), and training systems to improve
 F-22 weapons, communications, navigation, pilot-vehicle interface, and electronic warfare suite.

 Funds may be used to resolve emerging safety of flight and diminishing manufacturing sources issues, accommodate technology insertion and fulfill Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) or other mandates
 necessary to ensure continued aircrew safety and mission effectiveness.

 The FY 2026 request was reduced by $2.201 million for Advisory and Assistance Services to promote efficiencies and advance the policies of the Administration in alignment with Executive Order 14222,
 Implementing the President's Department of Government Efficiency Cost Efficiency Initiative.

 Funding for this exhibit contained in Program (PE) 0207138F.

 In accordance with Section 1815 of the FY08 National Defense Authorization Act (P.L. 110-181), this item is necessary for use by the active and reserve components of the Armed Forces for homeland defense
 missions, domestic emergency responses, and providing military support to civil authorities.$$, $$$$, $${"bucket":"fy26_specific_pb_v43","method":"direct_li_with_title_overlap","rapidfuzz_score":100.0,"src_li":46,"src_title":"F-22A","supersedes":"fy26_pointing_at_fy27_pb_placeholder","applied_at":"2026-05-09T_v196b"}$$, $$Budget J-Books/FY26/USAF/FY26 Air Force Aircraft Procurement Vol II.pdf$$, 289, 289, $$d4c442b408dc16a2$$, $$2026-05-10T02:12:16.956197+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_1109_L002$$, 2026, $$As a linchpin program for the Commandant of the Marine Corps' Force Design initiative, the Amphibious Combat Vehicle (ACV) has been purposefully built to deliver a warfighting advantage. It provides critical
 protected mobility to our dismounted warfighter, empowering them to execute seamless littoral maneuvers from ship-to-shore and across contested coastlines. Equipped with modern communication systems and
 weapons for infantry support-by-fire, the ACV significantly improves the ability of Fleet Marine Forces to access, seize, and hold key maritime terrain in the execution of Expeditionary Advanced Base Operations.
 It directly enables our ability to project power from the sea and guarantees joint freedom of maneuver against sophisticated anti-access/area denial strategies in regions vital to our national interest. The ACV
 provides commanders with expanded operational and tactical options, enabling the rapid transition of combat power from sea to land. This capability allows for swift crisis response, creates pathways for joint
 follow-on forces, and imposes disproportionate costs on adversaries who must extend their defenses. The program has successfully delivered the initial capability for the Personnel variant (ACV-P) in November
 2020 and the Command variant (ACV-C) in October 2024. It remains on track to field the enhanced firepower of the 30mm cannon variant (ACV-30) in the third quarter of FY 2026, followed by the Recovery
 variant (ACV-R) in the third quarter of FY 2028.

 The ACV Family of Vehicles (FoV) replaces the legacy Assault Amphibious Vehicle (AAV), mitigating critical capability gaps by providing a transformational leap in force protection and survivability against blast,
 fragmentation, and kinetic energy threats. This advanced, eight-wheeled platform delivers superior land and water mobility and significantly improved lethality against enemy forces, ensuring that ACV-equipped
 companies can provide secure, protected lift for our Marine Infantry battalions.

 The initial ACV procurement increment, from FY 2018 to FY 2021, focused on delivering the Personnel variant to empower Marines to mass at littoral penetration points and advance on inland objectives.
 Subsequent procurements, planned from FY 2022 to FY 2026, are expanding the fleet of personnel carriers while introducing command and control, improved lethality, and tactical recovery variants.

 This phased approach was solidified by key acquisition decisions. An Acquisition Decision Memorandum (ADM) from the Assistant Secretary of the Navy for Research, Development and Acquisition
 (ASN(RD&A)) on 8 January 2019 formally combined the ACV 1.1 and 1.2 efforts into a single ACV FoV program. Following this, an ADM on 12 July 2019 authorized a third lot of low-rate initial production (LRIP)
 consisting of 56 vehicles. These updates to the FY 2020 acquisition strategy culminated in the procurement of the first lot of full-rate production in FY 2021, ensuring a steady delivery of this vital capability to the
 fleet.

 The FY 2026 spend plan amount for Procurement Marine Corps Amphibious Combat Vehicles include $780,296 thousands of discretionary and $241,000 thousands of mandatory (reconciliation) for a total of
 $1,021,296 thousands.$$, NULL, $$Exhibit P-40, Budget Line Item Justification: PB 2027 Navy                                                                                                                     Date: April 2026
