 Description:
 Marine Corps Enterprise Network (MCEN) resources are foundational to Force Design and are a critical enabler for executing the Marine Corps Network Implementation Plan and the Marine Corps Cyberspace
 Environment Convergence Strategy, which is the strategic vision of the Marine Corps' single global warfighting network. Investments sustain and increase operational readiness and reduce cyber vulnerabilities
 throughout the MCEN. Funding enables the Marine Corps to operate its network effectively to achieve Zero Trust, defend its network against cyber-attacks, and effectively mitigate cyber vulnerabilities.
 Additionally, a secure and modern network is foundational for enabling cloud migration, machine learning, and artificial intelligence initiatives that are a critical component of Force Design.

 Enterprise IT Network Infrastructure provides the network infrastructure, fielding resources, engineering expertise, and lifecycle sustainment for dynamic, resilient, secure network and voice solutions. These
 solutions contribute to the availability of Assured Command and Control (C2) to Department services, National Security Systems, USMC core networks (NIPRNet and SIPRNet) globally from garrison to the
 tactical edge. Materiel solutions are inclusive of unclassified and classified wired and wireless capabilities for Local Area Network (LAN) and Wide Area Network (WAN) transport, extension of enterprise services
 to the tactical edge, data network circuits, secure network management solutions, and infrastructure modernization/refresh. This line item includes funding specified for Defense Policy Review Initiative (DPRI)
 within the above details.

 Enterprise IT Security and Compliance provide resources related to IT security compliance and disaster recovery. This includes resources to set policy, establish processes and means, measure compliance,
 meet relevant legal/compliance requirements (e.g., Data Privacy, multi-factor authentication, etc.), and respond to security breaches and provide real-time operational security measures such as vulnerability
 scanning, management of firewalls, and intrusion prevention systems. In addition, this program provides resources to set disaster recovery policy, establishing processes and means, and performing disaster
 recovery testing (note: this does not include resources for disaster relief facility or servers for disaster relief facilities).

 Enterprise IT End User Devices and Services funds and manages the resources to procure, operate, refresh, sustain and administer end user devices. End user devices include enterprise business workplace
 devices (e.g., desktops, laptops, ruggedized laptops, tablets, ruggedized tablets and thin or zero client machines), mobile devices managed by the Microsoft Intune container (e.g., tablets, 2-in-1 devices, and the
 Intune container for Government furnished smartphones), and the corresponding Marine Corps Enterprise Desktop Standard (MCEDS) Image based on windows operating systems.




