INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_1109_L030$$, 2026, $$FORMAL SCHOOLS TECHNICAL REFRESH (FSTR):
 The FSTR program is responsible for the procurement, deployment, and lifecycle management of Information Technology (IT) hardware and software critical to the delivery of Computer-Based Training (CBT)
 capabilities throughout Training and Education Command (TECOM) schools and Formal Learning Centers (FLCs). Unlike Marine Corps Enterprise Network (MCEN) End User Devices (EUDs), FSTR-funded
 EUDs are dedicated exclusively to TECOM instructional environments and operate on an independent hardware refresh cycle tailored to training requirements.

 Currently, FSTR standardizes IT assets across 812 TECOM classrooms, institutionalizing a consistent upgrade and refresh schedule, where "refresh" encompasses both the hardware upgrade and the technical
 software update of devices to ensure optimal performance, security, and compliance. The program has expanded its scope to encompass software provisioning, including funding for the Marine Corps Enterprise
 Desktop Solution (MCEDS) baseline image, with future potential requirements anticipated for student-specific software licenses to support diverse training personas.

 Given the high turnover rates inherent in the student population and the imperative for sustained software compliance and system reliability, a three-year refresh cycle for FSTR EUDs has been established as
 optimal. This cycle diverges from the standard MCEN EUD refresh interval of five years, which does not sufficiently address the unique operational demands of TECOM's training environments.

 FSTR directly underpins the delivery of Marine Corps Programs of Instruction (POI) within TECOM FLCs and constitutes a foundational element in realizing the Commandant's vision for technologically enhanced
 Training & Education as articulated in Force Design (FD) and Training & Education 2030 (TE2030) initiatives.

 MARINE CORPS INFORMATION OPERATIONS PROGRAM (MCIOP):
 The Marine Corps Information Operations Program delivers comprehensive, real-time Information Battlespace awareness to enable and support information-related activities, influence operations, and
 operational planning, including rigorous assessment and analysis. The program provides mission-tailored support at both tactical and operational echelons via task-organized teams and integrated reach-back
 capabilities. These support elements directly assist Service Headquarters, Service Components, Joint Force commands, Interagency partners, and Partner Nations across a full spectrum of Operations, Activities,
 and Investments (OAIs).

